      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans.&nbsp;B) Glycopyrrolate</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B: </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Glycopyrrolate </strong>is <strong>not a tertiary amine;</strong> it is a <strong>quaternary ammonium compound. Tertiary amines</strong> have the ability to<strong> cross the blood-brain barrier </strong>due to their structure, whereas <strong>quaternary ammonium compounds</strong>, such <strong>as glycopyrrolate</strong>, are<strong> unable to cross </strong>due to their <strong>charged nature.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong><u> </u></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A. Atropine</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> - <strong>Incorrect</strong>, as it is a<strong> tertiary amine</strong> and <strong>can cross the blood-brain barrier,</strong> leading to <strong>central effects. </strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C. Scopolamine</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> - <strong>Incorrect,</strong> as it is a <strong>tertiary amine</strong> with <strong>central effects</strong> and is also known as <strong>hyoscine. </strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D. Hyoscine</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> - <strong>Incorrect, </strong>as it is <strong>another name for scopolamine</strong>, a<strong> tertiary amine </strong>with<strong> central actions.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational objective:</span></u></strong><u> </u></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Glycopyrrolate</strong> is a <strong>quaternary ammonium compound,</strong> which <strong>cannot cross the blood-brain barrier,</strong> distinguishing it from <strong>tertiary</strong> <strong>amines </strong>like <strong>atropine and scopolamine (also known as hyoscine),</strong> which can have <strong>central nervous system effects.</strong></span></span></span></p>",
