      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. A) Hypoglycemia</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Salmeterol </strong>is a <strong>beta 2 agonist.</strong> It can result in <strong>tachycardia, tremors and hypokalemia</strong> but <strong>not hypoglycemia.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Beta-2 agonists</strong> like <strong>salmeterol</strong> can lead to <strong>hypokalemia</strong> due to <strong>intracellular shifting of potassium.</strong> They can also cause<strong> tremors </strong>due to <strong>stimulation of beta-2 receptors in the skeletal muscles</strong> and <strong>tachycardia</strong> by affecting the <strong>heart.</strong> However, they<strong> do not</strong> typically cause<strong> hypoglycemia</strong>, which is <strong>more </strong>commonly associated with <strong>insulin </strong>or other <strong>glucose-lowering medications.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Option B.</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Hypokalemia:</strong> Can occur <strong>due to the intracellular shifting of potassium ions. </strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Option C.</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Tachycardia:</strong> Can result from<strong> beta-2 stimulation in the heart</strong>, leading to<strong> increased heart rate. </strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Option D.</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Tremors:</strong> Are a common side effect <strong>due to stimulation of beta-2 receptors</strong> in the <strong>skeletal muscles.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational objective:</span></u></strong><u> </u></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Salmeterol,</strong> as a <strong>beta-2 agonist,</strong> <strong>does not</strong> typically cause <strong>hypoglycemia;</strong> its adverse effects related to <strong>beta-2 stimulation</strong> include <strong>tremors, tachycardia, and hypokalemia. </strong>Always monitor these potential side effects when prescribing or using beta-2 agonists.</span></span></p>",
